<paragraph blockId="7.[136,1452,158,869]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">
As 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cleve" authorityYear="1894" baseAuthorityName="W. Sm." box="[175,351,159,185]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Pleurosigmataceae" genus="Gyrosigma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="tenuissimum">
<emphasis box="[175,351,159,185]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">G. tenuissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with comparable striation (
<figureCitation box="[671,797,158,184]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–36" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1734,1756]" captionTargetBox="[255,1332,195,1687]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[250,1338,190,1713]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 28–36. Gyrosigma tenuissimum var. gundulae, type material. Figures 28, 30, 31. LM images. Fig. 28. Holotype, general view. Stitch of 5 stacks of 15–20 images each. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 30. Enlargement showing centre, note resolution of vestigial (upper) and continuous (lower) central bars. Bar = 1 µm. Fig. 31. Apex showing irregular striation. Bar = 3 µm. Figures 29, 32–36. SEM images. Fig.29. General view. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 32. Apex, external view. Arrow indicates small accessory pore. Bar = 3 µm. Fig. 33. Centre, external view. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement of Fig. 33 showing overlapping central raphe fissures. Fig. 34. Apex, internal view. Bar = 3 µm. Fig 35. Centre, internal view. Note sideways twisting of raphe fissures. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement showing vestigial central bars. Fig. 36. Vestigial central bars of another specimen. Bar = 1.5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5142357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5142357/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Fig. 28, 30</figureCitation>
) but much more robust and larger: 159–190 µm long and 9.5–11 µm wide. With respect to 
<taxonomicName authority="var. tenuissimum" box="[515,887,195,221]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Pleurosigmataceae" genus="Gyrosigma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="tenuissimum" variety="tenuissimum">
<emphasis box="[515,690,195,221]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">G. tenuissimum</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[747,887,195,220]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">tenuissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, valve much broader at apices (
<figureCitation box="[1248,1380,194,220]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–36" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1734,1756]" captionTargetBox="[255,1332,195,1687]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[250,1338,190,1713]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 28–36. Gyrosigma tenuissimum var. gundulae, type material. Figures 28, 30, 31. LM images. Fig. 28. Holotype, general view. Stitch of 5 stacks of 15–20 images each. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 30. Enlargement showing centre, note resolution of vestigial (upper) and continuous (lower) central bars. Bar = 1 µm. Fig. 31. Apex showing irregular striation. Bar = 3 µm. Figures 29, 32–36. SEM images. Fig.29. General view. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 32. Apex, external view. Arrow indicates small accessory pore. Bar = 3 µm. Fig. 33. Centre, external view. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement of Fig. 33 showing overlapping central raphe fissures. Fig. 34. Apex, internal view. Bar = 3 µm. Fig 35. Centre, internal view. Note sideways twisting of raphe fissures. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement showing vestigial central bars. Fig. 36. Vestigial central bars of another specimen. Bar = 1.5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5142357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5142357/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Figs 32, 34</figureCitation>
), with presence of small accessory apical pore (
<figureCitation box="[605,690,230,256]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–36" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1734,1756]" captionTargetBox="[255,1332,195,1687]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[250,1338,190,1713]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 28–36. Gyrosigma tenuissimum var. gundulae, type material. Figures 28, 30, 31. LM images. Fig. 28. Holotype, general view. Stitch of 5 stacks of 15–20 images each. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 30. Enlargement showing centre, note resolution of vestigial (upper) and continuous (lower) central bars. Bar = 1 µm. Fig. 31. Apex showing irregular striation. Bar = 3 µm. Figures 29, 32–36. SEM images. Fig.29. General view. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 32. Apex, external view. Arrow indicates small accessory pore. Bar = 3 µm. Fig. 33. Centre, external view. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement of Fig. 33 showing overlapping central raphe fissures. Fig. 34. Apex, internal view. Bar = 3 µm. Fig 35. Centre, internal view. Note sideways twisting of raphe fissures. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement showing vestigial central bars. Fig. 36. Vestigial central bars of another specimen. Bar = 1.5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5142357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5142357/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
, arrow). Externally, central raphe fissures (
<figureCitation box="[1183,1271,230,256]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–36" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1734,1756]" captionTargetBox="[255,1332,195,1687]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[250,1338,190,1713]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 28–36. Gyrosigma tenuissimum var. gundulae, type material. Figures 28, 30, 31. LM images. Fig. 28. Holotype, general view. Stitch of 5 stacks of 15–20 images each. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 30. Enlargement showing centre, note resolution of vestigial (upper) and continuous (lower) central bars. Bar = 1 µm. Fig. 31. Apex showing irregular striation. Bar = 3 µm. Figures 29, 32–36. SEM images. Fig.29. General view. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 32. Apex, external view. Arrow indicates small accessory pore. Bar = 3 µm. Fig. 33. Centre, external view. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement of Fig. 33 showing overlapping central raphe fissures. Fig. 34. Apex, internal view. Bar = 3 µm. Fig 35. Centre, internal view. Note sideways twisting of raphe fissures. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement showing vestigial central bars. Fig. 36. Vestigial central bars of another specimen. Bar = 1.5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5142357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5142357/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Figs 33</figureCitation>
) identical to 
<taxonomicName authority="var. tenuissimum" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Pleurosigmataceae" genus="Gyrosigma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="tenuissimum" variety="tenuissimum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">G. tenuissimum</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[336,476,267,292]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">tenuissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Some external areolar fissures of adjacent rows show tendency to fuse, forming the letter 
<collectionCode box="[200,220,303,329]" country="Canada" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:13946" name="Royal British Columbia Museum - Herbarium" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" type="Museum">V</collectionCode>
(
<figureCitation box="[235,318,302,328]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–36" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1734,1756]" captionTargetBox="[255,1332,195,1687]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[250,1338,190,1713]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 28–36. Gyrosigma tenuissimum var. gundulae, type material. Figures 28, 30, 31. LM images. Fig. 28. Holotype, general view. Stitch of 5 stacks of 15–20 images each. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 30. Enlargement showing centre, note resolution of vestigial (upper) and continuous (lower) central bars. Bar = 1 µm. Fig. 31. Apex showing irregular striation. Bar = 3 µm. Figures 29, 32–36. SEM images. Fig.29. General view. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 32. Apex, external view. Arrow indicates small accessory pore. Bar = 3 µm. Fig. 33. Centre, external view. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement of Fig. 33 showing overlapping central raphe fissures. Fig. 34. Apex, internal view. Bar = 3 µm. Fig 35. Centre, internal view. Note sideways twisting of raphe fissures. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement showing vestigial central bars. Fig. 36. Vestigial central bars of another specimen. Bar = 1.5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5142357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5142357/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
), as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cleve" authorityYear="1894" baseAuthorityName="W. Sm." box="[398,572,303,329]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Pleurosigmataceae" genus="Gyrosigma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="tenuissimum">
<emphasis box="[398,572,303,329]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">G. tenuissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Internal raphe fissures show sideways twisting (
<figureCitation box="[1123,1207,302,329]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–36" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1734,1756]" captionTargetBox="[255,1332,195,1687]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[250,1338,190,1713]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 28–36. Gyrosigma tenuissimum var. gundulae, type material. Figures 28, 30, 31. LM images. Fig. 28. Holotype, general view. Stitch of 5 stacks of 15–20 images each. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 30. Enlargement showing centre, note resolution of vestigial (upper) and continuous (lower) central bars. Bar = 1 µm. Fig. 31. Apex showing irregular striation. Bar = 3 µm. Figures 29, 32–36. SEM images. Fig.29. General view. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 32. Apex, external view. Arrow indicates small accessory pore. Bar = 3 µm. Fig. 33. Centre, external view. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement of Fig. 33 showing overlapping central raphe fissures. Fig. 34. Apex, internal view. Bar = 3 µm. Fig 35. Centre, internal view. Note sideways twisting of raphe fissures. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement showing vestigial central bars. Fig. 36. Vestigial central bars of another specimen. Bar = 1.5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5142357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5142357/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[136,1452,158,869]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">
Central bars around internal central raphe node markedly variable in their degree of silification but are often vestigial, reduced to 4 small “knobs” of silica (
<figureCitation box="[669,843,374,401]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–36" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1734,1756]" captionTargetBox="[255,1332,195,1687]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[250,1338,190,1713]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 28–36. Gyrosigma tenuissimum var. gundulae, type material. Figures 28, 30, 31. LM images. Fig. 28. Holotype, general view. Stitch of 5 stacks of 15–20 images each. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 30. Enlargement showing centre, note resolution of vestigial (upper) and continuous (lower) central bars. Bar = 1 µm. Fig. 31. Apex showing irregular striation. Bar = 3 µm. Figures 29, 32–36. SEM images. Fig.29. General view. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 32. Apex, external view. Arrow indicates small accessory pore. Bar = 3 µm. Fig. 33. Centre, external view. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement of Fig. 33 showing overlapping central raphe fissures. Fig. 34. Apex, internal view. Bar = 3 µm. Fig 35. Centre, internal view. Note sideways twisting of raphe fissures. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement showing vestigial central bars. Fig. 36. Vestigial central bars of another specimen. Bar = 1.5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5142357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5142357/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Figs 35 and 36</figureCitation>
). The extreme resolution of the special LM technique used reveals that one central bar (the lower in 
<figureCitation box="[659,740,410,436]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–36" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1734,1756]" captionTargetBox="[255,1332,195,1687]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[250,1338,190,1713]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 28–36. Gyrosigma tenuissimum var. gundulae, type material. Figures 28, 30, 31. LM images. Fig. 28. Holotype, general view. Stitch of 5 stacks of 15–20 images each. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 30. Enlargement showing centre, note resolution of vestigial (upper) and continuous (lower) central bars. Bar = 1 µm. Fig. 31. Apex showing irregular striation. Bar = 3 µm. Figures 29, 32–36. SEM images. Fig.29. General view. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 32. Apex, external view. Arrow indicates small accessory pore. Bar = 3 µm. Fig. 33. Centre, external view. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement of Fig. 33 showing overlapping central raphe fissures. Fig. 34. Apex, internal view. Bar = 3 µm. Fig 35. Centre, internal view. Note sideways twisting of raphe fissures. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement showing vestigial central bars. Fig. 36. Vestigial central bars of another specimen. Bar = 1.5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5142357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5142357/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
) may also consist of a continuous sharp ridge, the other (upper in 
<figureCitation box="[167,249,446,472]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–36" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1734,1756]" captionTargetBox="[255,1332,195,1687]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[250,1338,190,1713]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 28–36. Gyrosigma tenuissimum var. gundulae, type material. Figures 28, 30, 31. LM images. Fig. 28. Holotype, general view. Stitch of 5 stacks of 15–20 images each. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 30. Enlargement showing centre, note resolution of vestigial (upper) and continuous (lower) central bars. Bar = 1 µm. Fig. 31. Apex showing irregular striation. Bar = 3 µm. Figures 29, 32–36. SEM images. Fig.29. General view. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 32. Apex, external view. Arrow indicates small accessory pore. Bar = 3 µm. Fig. 33. Centre, external view. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement of Fig. 33 showing overlapping central raphe fissures. Fig. 34. Apex, internal view. Bar = 3 µm. Fig 35. Centre, internal view. Note sideways twisting of raphe fissures. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement showing vestigial central bars. Fig. 36. Vestigial central bars of another specimen. Bar = 1.5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5142357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5142357/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
) being reduced to two separate “knobs”, which matches the aspect seen in 
<figureCitation box="[1116,1183,446,473]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–23" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1808,1830]" captionText="FIGURES 1–23. Gyrosigma tenuissimum." pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="var. tenuissimum" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Pleurosigmataceae" genus="Gyrosigma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="tenuissimum" variety="tenuissimum">
<emphasis box="[1225,1401,447,473]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">G. tenuissimum</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[136,276,483,508]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">tenuissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="78" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[136,1452,158,869]" box="[189,1389,518,545]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,356,518,544]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Etymology:—</emphasis>
The epithet refers to the long-term support of the first author’s diatom studies by his spouse.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[136,1452,158,869]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,281,554,580]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Habitat</emphasis>
:—Found at temperatures of 21.9–30.5° C and salinities of 26.2–38.9 PSU; typical spring and summer conditions. The Indian River Lagoon is quite shallow (
<bibRefCitation author="Hargraves, P. E. &amp; Hanisak, M. D." box="[748,1065,590,616]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" pagination="151 - 167" refId="ref5174" refString="Hargraves, P. E. &amp; Hanisak, M. D. (2011) The significance of chlorophyll size fractionation in the Indian River Lagoon, Florida. Florida Scientist 74: 151 - 167." type="journal article" year="2011">Hargraves &amp; Hanisak, 2011</bibRefCitation>
), so that the presence of this taxon in plankton samples is not by itself indicative of a planktonic habitat.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="78" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[136,1452,158,869]" box="[189,1248,662,689]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,335,662,688]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Distribution</emphasis>
:—Subtropical Indian River Lagoon, East coast of 
<collectingRegion box="[905,990,662,688]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Florida</collectingRegion>
: widespread (but rare).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[136,1452,158,869]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,385,698,724]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Observations:—</emphasis>
The vestigial central bars (4 “knobs”) match the situation in a specimen from the Adriatic illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Hobel, H. &amp; Sterrenburg, F. A. S." box="[292,616,734,760]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" pagination="13 - 19" refId="ref5249" refString="Hobel, H. &amp; Sterrenburg, F. A. S. (2011). UV photomicrography of diatoms, Diatom Research, 26: 1, 13 - 19 http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 0269249 x. 2011.587642" type="journal article" year="2011">Höbel &amp; Sterrenburg (2011</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation box="[631,716,734,760]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–23" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1808,1830]" captionText="FIGURES 1–23. Gyrosigma tenuissimum." pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
) that conforms to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cleve" authorityYear="1894" baseAuthorityName="W. Sm." box="[938,1117,735,761]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Pleurosigmataceae" genus="Gyrosigma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="tenuissimum">
<emphasis box="[938,1117,735,761]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">G. tenuissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The central bars are highly variable in shape in both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cleve" authorityYear="1894" baseAuthorityName="W. Sm." box="[420,595,771,797]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Pleurosigmataceae" genus="Gyrosigma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="tenuissimum">
<emphasis box="[420,595,771,797]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">G. tenuissimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the 
<taxonomicName box="[692,884,770,796]" pageId="7" pageNumber="78" rank="variety" variety="described">variety described</taxonomicName>
here. Deposition of silica is a quantitative process and marked variation in the solidity of the central bars is common in the genus. Probably the basic shape in the taxa discussed is as in 
<figureCitation box="[335,401,842,869]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–23" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1808,1830]" captionText="FIGURES 1–23. Gyrosigma tenuissimum." pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[455,485,842,868]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–36" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1734,1756]" captionTargetBox="[255,1332,195,1687]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[250,1338,190,1713]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 28–36. Gyrosigma tenuissimum var. gundulae, type material. Figures 28, 30, 31. LM images. Fig. 28. Holotype, general view. Stitch of 5 stacks of 15–20 images each. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 30. Enlargement showing centre, note resolution of vestigial (upper) and continuous (lower) central bars. Bar = 1 µm. Fig. 31. Apex showing irregular striation. Bar = 3 µm. Figures 29, 32–36. SEM images. Fig.29. General view. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 32. Apex, external view. Arrow indicates small accessory pore. Bar = 3 µm. Fig. 33. Centre, external view. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement of Fig. 33 showing overlapping central raphe fissures. Fig. 34. Apex, internal view. Bar = 3 µm. Fig 35. Centre, internal view. Note sideways twisting of raphe fissures. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement showing vestigial central bars. Fig. 36. Vestigial central bars of another specimen. Bar = 1.5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5142357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5142357/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">30</figureCitation>
, reduction leading to the aspect as in 
<figureCitation box="[905,1074,842,869]" captionStart="FIGURES 28–36" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1734,1756]" captionTargetBox="[255,1332,195,1687]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[250,1338,190,1713]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 28–36. Gyrosigma tenuissimum var. gundulae, type material. Figures 28, 30, 31. LM images. Fig. 28. Holotype, general view. Stitch of 5 stacks of 15–20 images each. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 30. Enlargement showing centre, note resolution of vestigial (upper) and continuous (lower) central bars. Bar = 1 µm. Fig. 31. Apex showing irregular striation. Bar = 3 µm. Figures 29, 32–36. SEM images. Fig.29. General view. Bar = 30 µm. Fig. 32. Apex, external view. Arrow indicates small accessory pore. Bar = 3 µm. Fig. 33. Centre, external view. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement of Fig. 33 showing overlapping central raphe fissures. Fig. 34. Apex, internal view. Bar = 3 µm. Fig 35. Centre, internal view. Note sideways twisting of raphe fissures. Bar = 3 µm. Inset: 1.5x enlargement showing vestigial central bars. Fig. 36. Vestigial central bars of another specimen. Bar = 1.5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5142357" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5142357/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="78">Figs 35 and 36</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
